00:09:00.030 --> 00:09:07.000
So as I was saying, I am so
pleased to be here today to share

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:12.030
with you this presentation about
the Judische Kulturbund Porject.

00:09:12.030 --> 00:09:16.480
It's a project I founded years
ago to tell the story of artists

00:09:16.480 --> 00:09:22.820 position:56%
and musicians responding to
oppression in the most powerful ways

00:09:22.820 --> 00:09:25.830
through their art and music.

00:09:25.830 --> 00:09:29.630
And I really love telling
this story.

00:09:29.630 --> 00:09:36.990
About 15 years ago, I learned
about the story of Jewish musicians

00:09:36.990 --> 00:09:42.170
and performing artists in Berlin
in 1933 when they were fired

00:09:42.170 --> 00:09:45.760
from their jobs in places
like the [inaudible],

00:09:45.760 --> 00:09:49.170
the Berlin Philharmonic,
and the state opera.

00:09:49.170 --> 00:09:52.360
They were fired because
they were Jews.

00:09:52.360 --> 00:09:57.900 position:56%
A small group of Jewish artists met,
and what they decided in response

00:09:57.900 --> 00:10:01.570
to their being fired
was extraordinary.

00:10:01.570 --> 00:10:06.220
Led by Kurt Singer, the artistic
director, they would propose

00:10:06.220 --> 00:10:10.780
to the Nazi that they organize
their own cultural association

00:10:10.780 --> 00:10:12.520
for Jews only.

00:10:12.520 --> 00:10:16.850
They would be self-sustaining
through membership subscriptions.

00:10:16.850 --> 00:10:19.300 position:56%
Kurt Singer delivered their proposal

00:10:19.300 --> 00:10:21.120
to Joseph Gerble's
[assumed spelling] office

00:10:21.120 --> 00:10:23.830
of propaganda and enlightenment.

00:10:23.830 --> 00:10:28.580
Surprisingly, the Nazis
approved the proposal.

00:10:28.580 --> 00:10:32.390
The Kulturbund understood that
the Nazis would oversee their

00:10:32.390 --> 00:10:37.040
organization and approve
of all their activities.

00:10:37.040 --> 00:10:42.300
And so in 1933, the
Kulturbund Deutscher Juden,

00:10:42.300 --> 00:10:46.160
the Jewish Cultural League
of German Jews, was born.

00:10:46.160 --> 00:10:53.510
And in 1936, the Nazis told the
Kulturbund to remove Deutscher,

00:10:53.510 --> 00:10:56.630
German, from the organization's
name.

00:10:56.630 --> 00:11:00.910
And so they became known
as the Judische Kulturbund,

00:11:00.910 --> 00:11:03.690
the Jewish Cultural Association.

00:11:03.690 --> 00:11:06.810
Now, I just showed you a
series of these pictures.

00:11:06.810 --> 00:11:09.750
They were actually
painted by a young woman,

00:11:09.750 --> 00:11:12.440
a teenager named Charlotte
Solomon who is

00:11:12.440 --> 00:11:16.280
from a prominent Jewish family
in Berlin, and her stepmother,

00:11:16.280 --> 00:11:20.630
Paula Lindberg, was an opera
singer in the Kulturbund.

00:11:20.630 --> 00:11:23.690
They sent her -- her father
and stepmother sent her

00:11:23.690 --> 00:11:27.680
to southern France where her
grandfather lived to hide

00:11:27.680 --> 00:11:32.680
between 1940 and '43 when she
painted hundreds of paintings

00:11:32.680 --> 00:11:34.640
about her life in Berlin.

00:11:34.640 --> 00:11:37.850
And some of them were
of the Kulturbund.

00:11:37.850 --> 00:11:44.480
Charlotte and her unborn child
were perished in Auschwitz in 1943.

00:11:44.480 --> 00:11:51.120
When the Kulturbund started in
1933, it opened in Berlin then soon

00:11:51.120 --> 00:11:55.800
after opened in 42
theaters around Germany.

00:11:55.800 --> 00:11:58.570
The Kulturbund performed operas,

00:11:58.570 --> 00:12:00.660
[inaudible], symphonies
and cabarets.

00:12:00.660 --> 00:12:04.870
Some of the finest
musicians in German remember.

00:12:04.870 --> 00:12:09.130
To give you an idea of the
size of the organization,

00:12:09.130 --> 00:12:11.780
they hired about 2000 artists.

00:12:11.780 --> 00:12:13.420
Hannah is one of them.

00:12:13.420 --> 00:12:17.350
And their membership swelled
to about 70,000 people.

00:12:17.350 --> 00:12:22.620
At its height in 1937,
there were 18,500 members

00:12:22.620 --> 00:12:24.860
in the Berlin Kulturbund alone.

00:12:24.860 --> 00:12:29.160
More than ten percent of
the Jewish population there.

00:12:29.160 --> 00:12:32.640
Since I learned the story, I
am still amazed by the idea

00:12:32.640 --> 00:12:35.890
of artists responding to
their expulsion from jobs

00:12:35.890 --> 00:12:40.850
in their homeland by organizing
as they did and then perplexed

00:12:40.850 --> 00:12:42.750
by the Nazi's sanctioning
their plan.

00:12:42.750 --> 00:12:47.540
On the one hand, the formation
of the Kulturbund was an act

00:12:47.540 --> 00:12:50.610
of defiance by the Jewish artists.

00:12:50.610 --> 00:12:51.910
And for some of the artists,

00:12:51.910 --> 00:12:55.080
they thought that they were
safe performing in a haven away

00:12:55.080 --> 00:12:58.680
from the darkness covering
outside the theater.

00:12:58.680 --> 00:13:02.450
For the Nazis, we believe
that the Kulturbund was used

00:13:02.450 --> 00:13:06.200
as a propaganda tool to tell the
world the Jews are doing fine

00:13:06.200 --> 00:13:10.750
and perhaps it was a way for
the Nazis to contain the Jews.

00:13:10.750 --> 00:13:15.230
It was certainly the beginning
of marginalizing, repressing

00:13:15.230 --> 00:13:18.880
and ultimately squeezing
them out of society.

00:13:18.880 --> 00:13:20.180
For the Kulturbund,

00:13:20.180 --> 00:13:24.290
did it ultimately prevent some
artists from leaving sooner?

00:13:24.290 --> 00:13:28.000
Did it provide them with
a false sense of security?

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:32.840
Or did it succeed in defying
the Nazis and provide a way

00:13:32.840 --> 00:13:34.890
for many artists to survive?

00:13:34.890 --> 00:13:38.610
Maybe the Kulturbund
were all of these things.

00:13:38.610 --> 00:13:42.430
I started this project to
capture these Kulturbund artists'

00:13:42.430 --> 00:13:44.340
experiences and issues

00:13:44.340 --> 00:13:48.120
and to explore how the
Kulturbund is relevant today.

00:13:48.120 --> 00:13:53.010
My first task was to interview as
many survivors as I could locate.

00:13:53.010 --> 00:13:54.850
I filmed 15 interviews.

00:13:54.850 --> 00:13:57.820
Most of these subjects
have since died.

00:13:57.820 --> 00:14:01.200
One of those I interviewed
attended a Kulturbund performance.

00:14:01.200 --> 00:14:04.400
She remembers seeing
Barbara Seville.

00:14:04.400 --> 00:14:08.230
I interviewed performers, an
actor, a dancer choreographer,

00:14:08.230 --> 00:14:11.230
Hannah, and several musicians.

00:14:11.230 --> 00:14:15.180
And I interviewed a seamstress
who altered the same costumes over

00:14:15.180 --> 00:14:19.000
and over again for
many performances.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:22.350
These interviews were very moving

00:14:22.350 --> 00:14:26.130
as the subjects described their
memories living in Germany,

00:14:26.130 --> 00:14:27.890
their experiences in the Kulturbund

00:14:27.890 --> 00:14:31.950
and the performances
in which they played.

00:14:31.950 --> 00:14:35.800
A common theme for all of them,
which Gail had said before,

00:14:35.800 --> 00:14:38.430
the power of music, the resiliency

00:14:38.430 --> 00:14:43.250
of the human spirit and
the will to survive.

00:14:43.250 --> 00:14:48.700
So Hannah was a choreographer
and a dancer

00:14:48.700 --> 00:14:53.040
in the Berlin Kulturbund
in 1938 and '39.

00:14:53.040 --> 00:14:56.480
She and her parents fled Germany

00:14:56.480 --> 00:15:00.690
for New York before the Nazis
stopped giving out Visas.

00:15:00.690 --> 00:15:03.250
After settling in America,

00:15:03.250 --> 00:15:05.920
Hannah founded the Hannah Koner
[assumed spelling] Dance Studio

00:15:05.920 --> 00:15:07.400
in Long Island.

00:15:07.400 --> 00:15:11.040
Hannah passed away last
year at the age of 95.

00:15:11.040 --> 00:15:14.540
Her legacy continues
through her children

00:15:14.540 --> 00:15:18.120 position:56%
and proteges in the U.S. and abroad.

00:15:18.120 --> 00:15:22.660
So to start her story,
I wanted to share

00:15:22.660 --> 00:15:26.300
with you a film interview excerpt.

00:15:26.300 --> 00:15:30.050
&gt;&gt; As the years went on, the world
of the Jews became [inaudible]

00:15:30.050 --> 00:15:35.640
and really there was no
way that anY Jew will end

00:15:35.640 --> 00:15:42.410
up in Berlin [inaudible] for
the whole country was able to go

00:15:42.410 --> 00:15:45.640
to any theater or to any movie.

00:15:45.640 --> 00:15:51.640
No television was here and radio
was only what the Nazis chose

00:15:51.640 --> 00:15:53.230
to present.

00:15:53.230 --> 00:15:57.510
So our world was totally
void of entertainment

00:15:57.510 --> 00:16:03.790
and the Kulturbund was
this in its best form.

00:16:03.790 --> 00:16:08.420
I would like to nowadays
tell people that if something

00:16:08.420 --> 00:16:13.680
like this would happen in
this country, God forbid,

00:16:13.680 --> 00:16:17.790
I'd imagine that all the top
artists of Lincoln Center,

00:16:17.790 --> 00:16:24.050
the Metropolitan Opera House,
movies, books, if everyone who is

00:16:24.050 --> 00:16:29.600
of Jewish religion or had one
Jewish grandparent would be totally

00:16:29.600 --> 00:16:33.440
prohibited to [inaudible]
their profession.

00:16:33.440 --> 00:16:38.670
And those people pulled themselves
together and formed the Kulturbund.

00:16:38.670 --> 00:16:42.750
&gt;&gt; Gail Prensky: Artists
of the Kulturbund

00:16:42.750 --> 00:16:46.480
like Hannah impacted not just
German and Jewish culture

00:16:46.480 --> 00:16:48.720
but culture in other lands.

00:16:48.720 --> 00:16:51.190
I want to share some of
these artists with you.

00:16:51.190 --> 00:16:54.840
I will also share video
excerpts of contemporary concerts

00:16:54.840 --> 00:16:58.090
that represent some of the
music the Kulturbund artists

00:16:58.090 --> 00:16:59.700
remember performing.

00:16:59.700 --> 00:17:03.440
I also want to add that for
each piece shared with you,

00:17:03.440 --> 00:17:07.400
these music compositions tell
stories and represent themes

00:17:07.400 --> 00:17:11.800
such as freedom, defiance
and resiliency.

00:17:11.800 --> 00:17:14.570
I can only guess that the
Kulturbund selected them

00:17:14.570 --> 00:17:18.470
because of their significance,
their meaning.

00:17:19.650 --> 00:17:21.750
Arence [assumed spelling]
Leonard was an actor

00:17:21.750 --> 00:17:26.090
who joined the Berlin
Kulturbund in 1933.

00:17:26.090 --> 00:17:28.870
Soon after Arence joined
the Kulturbund,

00:17:28.870 --> 00:17:31.470
he performed in their first
production in October,

00:17:31.470 --> 00:17:37.140
1933 in the theater on
[inaudible] in Berlin.

00:17:37.140 --> 00:17:43.040 position:56%
It was a play called Nathan the Wise
written by Gotthold Ephraim Lessing.

00:17:43.040 --> 00:17:48.400
Nathan the Wise is a story about
religious tolerance among Muslims,

00:17:48.400 --> 00:17:53.200
Christians and Jews in Jerusalem
during the 12th century's

00:17:53.200 --> 00:17:55.180
third crusade.

00:17:55.180 --> 00:17:58.450
When the Nazis saw the
performance, they shut it down,

00:17:58.450 --> 00:18:01.850
never allowing the
Kulturbund to perform it again.

00:18:01.850 --> 00:18:06.010
In 1936, Arence left for New York

00:18:06.010 --> 00:18:08.630
where he met William
Morris, the agent.

00:18:08.630 --> 00:18:12.930
Then he moved to Hollywood where
he acted and became a photographer,

00:18:12.930 --> 00:18:15.480
devleoping the first screen tests.

00:18:15.480 --> 00:18:19.750
His first client was Tony Curtis.

00:18:19.750 --> 00:18:24.030
His last performance in
2004, a year before he died,

00:18:24.030 --> 00:18:28.550
was a German Israeli
co-production called Walk on Water.

00:18:28.550 --> 00:18:30.500
He called me when he got the part.

00:18:30.500 --> 00:18:35.390
He was so excited about the
opportunity to be in a movie again.

00:18:35.390 --> 00:18:43.260
"Imagine the irony, he said, I am
playing, wait, a Nazi perpetrator."

00:18:43.260 --> 00:18:46.150
And we laughed.

00:18:46.150 --> 00:18:49.360
Yuri Tepletts [assumed spelling]
was a flutist joining the Frankfurt

00:18:49.360 --> 00:18:52.030
Kulturbund in 1934.

00:18:52.030 --> 00:18:53.670
One of the first performances

00:18:53.670 --> 00:18:57.450
in which he played was
Mendelson's violin concerto.

00:18:57.450 --> 00:19:01.470
It was a special piece because
the German orchestras no longer

00:19:01.470 --> 00:19:03.650
played Mendelson.

00:19:03.650 --> 00:19:06.270
The reason was that
the orchestra's --

00:19:06.270 --> 00:19:09.250
the reason that the orchestra
did not play Mendelson is

00:19:09.250 --> 00:19:12.790
because the Nazis believed
he was a Jew.

00:19:12.790 --> 00:19:17.650
While Mendelson's family were
Jewish, he was baptized Christian.

00:19:17.650 --> 00:19:21.450
It did not matter his
blood line was Jewish.

00:19:21.450 --> 00:19:24.820
I'm going to share
with you now an excerpt

00:19:24.820 --> 00:19:28.850
of Mendelson's violin concerto,
and [inaudible] is on violin

00:19:28.850 --> 00:19:31.790
and Curt Mazer [assumed
spelling] is conducting.

