others from the Frankfurt Kulturbund

00:21:10.850 --> 00:21:16.960
to help start the Bronislaw
Hooverman's Palestine Symphony

00:21:16.960 --> 00:21:21.890
Orchestra, which is today
the Israeli Philharmonic.

00:21:21.890 --> 00:21:23.800
Margalite Waxman [assumed
spelling] was the daughter

00:21:23.800 --> 00:21:28.160
of the founding artistic director
of the Kulturbund Kurt Singer.

00:21:28.160 --> 00:21:32.490
She attended many of her father's
concerts and remembers in '36

00:21:32.490 --> 00:21:37.020
when the Kulturbund began
performing Yiddish plays and music.

00:21:37.020 --> 00:21:39.750
This was an extraordinary event.

00:21:39.750 --> 00:21:44.040
Up until that time, the Kulturbund
played music by the great composers

00:21:44.040 --> 00:21:49.100
of Europe, Bach, Beethoven, Bram,
Schubert, [inaudible] and Mozart.

00:21:49.100 --> 00:21:52.550
But in '36, the Nazis
instructed the Kulturbund

00:21:52.550 --> 00:21:56.660
that they could no longer
play music -- I'm sorry --

00:21:56.660 --> 00:22:02.700
perform music or dramas
composed by Austrians or Germans.

00:22:02.700 --> 00:22:06.690
The play only works by
Jewish or foreign composers.

00:22:06.690 --> 00:22:09.250
Beethoven, Mozart and
Haydn were out.

00:22:09.250 --> 00:22:12.550
Moller and Mendelson were in.

00:22:12.550 --> 00:22:14.460
They needed to expand
their repertoire

00:22:14.460 --> 00:22:17.710
so they started researching and
learning about Yiddish music

00:22:17.710 --> 00:22:21.350
and dramas about which
they knew little.

00:22:21.350 --> 00:22:23.830
One such piece was a
liturgical song, [inaudible].

00:22:23.830 --> 00:22:28.660
[Inaudible] performing [inaudible]
in Amsterdam's Portuguese --

00:22:28.660 --> 00:22:35.430
Amsterdam's Portuguese Synagog.

00:22:36.510 --> 00:24:38.130
[ Music ]

00:24:38.130 --> 00:24:41.050
Wasn't it great?

00:24:41.050 --> 00:24:45.160 position:56%
Margalite's father, Kurt Singer,
was passionate about the Kulturbund.

00:24:45.160 --> 00:24:49.620
In fact, he believed that he
and the Kulturbund were special

00:24:49.620 --> 00:24:52.010
and protected by the Nazis.

00:24:52.010 --> 00:24:55.790
In 1938, he left Berlin for
the Netherlands and then went

00:24:55.790 --> 00:25:01.340
on to the United States to visit
his sister and lecturer at Harvard.

00:25:01.340 --> 00:25:05.530
Singer was also lecturing in New
York's Young Hebrew Association

00:25:05.530 --> 00:25:09.340
and was given an offer
for a permanent post

00:25:09.340 --> 00:25:11.380
at Yale, which he turned down.

00:25:11.380 --> 00:25:14.380
He couldn't shake his
commitment to the Kulturbund

00:25:14.380 --> 00:25:16.950
and wanted to return to Berlin.

00:25:16.950 --> 00:25:18.560
The actor, Aaron Flenard
[assumed spelling],

00:25:18.560 --> 00:25:21.120
visited him in New York
telling Singer about [inaudible]

00:25:21.120 --> 00:25:28.170
and begged him to stay in the U.S.
Singer told his friend he must go

00:25:28.170 --> 00:25:31.010
back, "to rescue what
could be rescued."

00:25:31.010 --> 00:25:34.400
On his way to Germany,
Singer stopped

00:25:34.400 --> 00:25:36.580
in Holland to see his friends.

00:25:36.580 --> 00:25:39.900
They persuaded him not
to return to Germany.

00:25:39.900 --> 00:25:42.400
He realized that Kulturbund
could not survive,

00:25:42.400 --> 00:25:45.720 position:56%
and he decided to stay in Amsterdam.

00:25:45.720 --> 00:25:49.300
After the Nazi's occupation in
Holland, Singer tried to return

00:25:49.300 --> 00:25:52.090
to the U.S., but he
couldn't get a Visa.

00:25:52.090 --> 00:25:53.990
Eventually, he was
sent to [inaudible]

00:25:53.990 --> 00:25:56.610
where he died from illness.

00:25:56.610 --> 00:26:00.260
Margalite, her mother and
sister immigrated to Jerusalem.

00:26:00.260 --> 00:26:04.790
Singer's grandchildren and great
grandchildren lived there today.

00:26:04.790 --> 00:26:10.560
Today, we are remembering
November 10, 1938, the second day

00:26:10.560 --> 00:26:14.290
of Kristallnacht, the
Night of Broken Glass.

00:26:14.290 --> 00:26:18.310 position:56%
Terror swept through Germany setting
synagogues on fire, killing hundreds

00:26:18.310 --> 00:26:22.480
of Jews, closing the businesses
and schools and sending tens

00:26:22.480 --> 00:26:25.830
of thousands of Jews
to concentration camps.

00:26:25.830 --> 00:26:31.290
But imagine, three days after
Kristallnacht on November 13,

00:26:31.290 --> 00:26:34.150
the Kulturbund reopened
its theaters.

00:26:34.150 --> 00:26:37.600
Max Ehrlich and Willie Rosen
resurrected the cabaret

00:26:37.600 --> 00:26:41.300
and comedy review they had
been running since October.

00:26:41.300 --> 00:26:44.900
This must have been an
exhilarating and uplifting event

00:26:44.900 --> 00:26:47.440
for the Jewish performers
and audience.

00:26:47.440 --> 00:26:53.190
Willie Rosen said, "One takes a
thin comedian and a fat comic.

00:26:53.190 --> 00:26:55.380
One adds a few pounds."

00:26:55.380 --> 00:26:59.560
I need to go back one.

00:26:59.560 --> 00:27:06.950
Okay. "One takes a thin
comedian and a fat comic.

00:27:06.950 --> 00:27:09.050 position:56%
One adds a few pounds of sex appeal.

00:27:09.050 --> 00:27:12.120
One adds a few comprehensible
melodies

00:27:12.120 --> 00:27:14.860
which the audience can
sing after the show.

00:27:14.860 --> 00:27:19.120
One adds a few old jokes from
which you cut off the beards.

00:27:19.120 --> 00:27:22.740
One takes a lot of new jokes
and some ornaments, red,

00:27:22.740 --> 00:27:25.710
green and blue lights,
blend them all together

00:27:25.710 --> 00:27:27.340
and the review is done."

00:27:27.340 --> 00:27:29.270
Hence, they named the cabaret

00:27:29.270 --> 00:27:33.520
and the comedy review
Gemischtes Kompolt,

00:27:33.520 --> 00:27:36.300
which means mixed fruit cocktail.

00:27:37.920 --> 00:27:42.780
Now, Sarah and Patrick will do
another performance for you,

00:27:42.780 --> 00:27:48.400
and this will be what
good would the moon be.

00:27:48.400 --> 00:27:51.550
I don't know how you're going
to say it in the other language,

00:27:51.550 --> 00:27:53.800
but it is a cabaret
song written by one

00:27:53.800 --> 00:27:56.510
of Germany's great
20th century composers,

00:27:56.510 --> 00:28:01.380
Kurt Vile who was a target of the
Nazis early on fleeing Germany

00:28:01.380 --> 00:28:04.450
in March, 1933 for Paris.

00:28:04.450 --> 00:28:06.750
Come on up.

00:28:12.210 --> 00:28:13.720
&gt;&gt; Sarah Baumbarten: So Kurt
Vile's [inaudible] premiered

00:28:13.720 --> 00:28:17.260
on Broadway in 1947.

00:28:17.260 --> 00:28:20.490
Therefore, it was not
performed by the Kulturbund.

00:28:20.490 --> 00:28:25.060
However, Vile's music was well
represented on their many programs.

00:28:25.060 --> 00:28:28.020
The aria, What Good Would the
Moon Be, addresses the importance

00:28:28.020 --> 00:28:30.530
of love over material things.

00:28:30.530 --> 00:28:34.450
After all, love is what
makes life worthwhile.

00:28:34.450 --> 00:28:37.730
In our context, this aria helps
us to realize that without love,

00:28:37.730 --> 00:28:41.570
the Judischle Kulturbund
would not have even existed.

00:28:41.570 --> 00:28:44.500
Because so many had a
love of music and followed

00:28:44.500 --> 00:28:47.840
through with keeping it accessible,
hundreds, perhaps thousands

00:28:47.840 --> 00:28:50.160
of people were able to trudge
through the years leading

00:28:50.160 --> 00:28:53.460
up to the Holocaust with
hope instead of with fear.

00:28:53.460 --> 00:28:56.970
So enjoy What Good
Would the Moon Be.

00:29:00.510 --> 00:31:15.510
[ Singing ]

00:31:15.510 --> 00:31:26.860
[ Applause ]

00:31:26.860 --> 00:31:30.220
&gt;&gt; Gail Prensky: Henry Meyer
played violin and viola

00:31:30.220 --> 00:31:35.480
for the Kulturbund
between 1939 and 1941.

00:31:35.480 --> 00:31:40.010
Henry met the conductor of the
Berlin Kulturbund, Rudolf Schwartz,

00:31:40.010 --> 00:31:43.980
at a bus stop in Berlin one
day and was invited to audition

00:31:43.980 --> 00:31:46.470
for the Kulturbund orchestra.

00:31:46.470 --> 00:31:50.230
Only 16 years old, he was
the youngest performer

00:31:50.230 --> 00:31:52.880
of the Berlin Kulturbund.

00:31:52.880 --> 00:31:57.130
Carl Nielsen's Inextinguishable
Symphony was the last performance

00:31:57.130 --> 00:32:00.590
of Kulturbund conducted
by Rudolf Schwartz.

00:32:00.590 --> 00:32:04.760
Nielsen wrote in his notes that
the symphony applies to that

00:32:04.760 --> 00:32:09.090
which is inextinguishable
and the will to live,

00:32:09.090 --> 00:32:13.070
which made it appropriate for the
Kulturbund to play the symphony

00:32:13.070 --> 00:32:19.590
on the day the organization
closed on September 11, 1941.

00:32:19.590 --> 00:32:22.040
This is an excerpt of
the symphony conducted

00:32:22.040 --> 00:32:24.670
by Simon Rattle [assumed
spelling] who was the protégé

00:32:24.670 --> 00:32:30.510
of Rudolf Schwartz when they worked
together in Birmingham, England.

00:32:30.510 --> 00:33:35.150
[ Music ]

00:33:35.150 --> 00:33:38.170
When the Kulturbund closed,
Henry like others who stayed

00:33:38.170 --> 00:33:41.830
with the orchestra until the
end was sent to the camps.

00:33:41.830 --> 00:33:44.360
He barely survived Auschwitz.

00:33:44.360 --> 00:33:47.100
He came to the U.S. where
he became a professor

00:33:47.100 --> 00:33:49.440
at the Cincinnati Conservatory
of Music,

00:33:49.440 --> 00:33:54.420
and was the founding member
of [inaudible] Quartet.

00:33:54.420 --> 00:33:58.430 position:56%
While the Kulturbund is a unique and
little known story about thousands

00:33:58.430 --> 00:34:01.330
of artists from one country
who organized in response

00:34:01.330 --> 00:34:06.130 position:56%
to the Nazi's oppression, repression
and near extinction, today's artists

00:34:06.130 --> 00:34:12.280
around the world also respond to
their oppression through their art.

00:34:12.280 --> 00:34:14.230
Malika Serabi [assumed
spelling] is one

00:34:14.230 --> 00:34:16.990 position:56%
of those artists who lives in India.

00:34:16.990 --> 00:34:21.810
She is an actor, a dancer,
an activist, what she likes

00:34:21.810 --> 00:34:24.430
to call herself an artivist.

00:34:24.430 --> 00:34:26.810
Malika is a champion, working

00:34:26.810 --> 00:34:29.940
with those cast aside
called The Untouchables,

00:34:29.940 --> 00:34:34.920
and fights for the rights of the
underdog through her performance,

00:34:34.920 --> 00:34:41.480
art and other activities for which
she has won many honors in India.

00:34:41.480 --> 00:34:46.510
Here is a sample of an interview
that I did with Malika in 2014.

00:34:46.510 --> 00:34:48.910
&gt;&gt; I just have continued
[inaudible] or just

00:34:48.910 --> 00:34:53.970
to say we do not accept
what is happening.

00:34:53.970 --> 00:35:02.630
And the early Jewish artists
during the Nazi regimen

00:35:02.630 --> 00:35:06.580
with which this project
started were doing that.

00:35:06.580 --> 00:35:08.680
They were saying there
is a beauty in music

00:35:08.680 --> 00:35:11.910
that goes beyond the [inaudible]
of the world around us.

00:35:11.910 --> 00:35:15.190
Beyond that the artists in
many different regimens,

00:35:15.190 --> 00:35:19.320
are actually using their art to
protest against the government

00:35:19.320 --> 00:35:23.210
in much more open ways,
and I think many

00:35:23.210 --> 00:35:25.790 position:56%
of us feel isolated from each other.

00:35:25.790 --> 00:35:29.620
We don't know who it is in
Afghanistan was doing similar work

00:35:29.620 --> 00:35:31.680
or who it is in Nigeria
who is doing similar work.

00:35:31.680 --> 00:35:34.230
And I think that this project
can bring those together

00:35:34.230 --> 00:35:35.590
in one platform.

00:35:35.590 --> 00:35:42.970
We will be creating a sorority
or fraternity of people

00:35:42.970 --> 00:35:45.440
who know are not alone, and I think
that's why this is so important.

00:35:45.440 --> 00:35:51.080
&gt;&gt; Gail Prensky: We want to explore
how artists today might connect

00:35:51.080 --> 00:35:54.540
to the Kulturbund and the issues
they face, the choice to stay

00:35:54.540 --> 00:36:00.380 position:56%
or leave their homeland and what the
ramifications of their choice means.

00:36:00.380 --> 00:36:03.080
We also want to look at
the issue of identity

00:36:03.080 --> 00:36:06.110
and the power of music and art.

00:36:06.110 --> 00:36:12.040
We have talked with 34 artists from
22 countries including Afghanistan,

00:36:12.040 --> 00:36:18.570 position:56%
Argentina, [inaudible], Cambodia,
Chile, Congo DRC, India, Iran, Mali,

00:36:18.570 --> 00:36:21.880
Niger, North Korea,
Pakistan, Shrilanka,

00:36:21.880 --> 00:36:24.740
Sweden, Uganda and Ukraine.

00:36:24.740 --> 00:36:27.110
While the Nazis did not
allow the Kulturbund

00:36:27.110 --> 00:36:30.260
to film their performances
or record their music,

00:36:30.260 --> 00:36:34.130
today we have the advantage
of technology and social media

00:36:34.130 --> 00:36:39.960 position:56%
that break down the barriers
despite dictator's efforts to squash

00:36:39.960 --> 00:36:45.860
or quash their attempts to let
the outside world know about them.

00:36:45.860 --> 00:36:47.790
I'd like to share with you examples

00:36:47.790 --> 00:36:52.410
of our collaborating
artists stories.

00:36:52.410 --> 00:36:55.350
This is Minera Hashami
[assumed spelling].

00:36:55.350 --> 00:36:59.570
She's a performing artist from
Afghanistan now exiled in Sweden

00:36:59.570 --> 00:37:02.980
as is one of her brothers
sand his family.

00:37:02.980 --> 00:37:07.360
Her parents, two sisters and
another brother live in Berlin.

00:37:07.360 --> 00:37:11.430
She and her family fled in 2012
after years of threats and abuse

00:37:11.430 --> 00:37:16.180
by the community, one, for being
[inaudible], two for being women

00:37:16.180 --> 00:37:19.980 position:56%
who worked outsidse the home and
three, working as performing artists

00:37:19.980 --> 00:37:24.580
which is akin to those in
Afghanistan as being prostitutes.

00:37:24.580 --> 00:37:26.610
Minera's mother encouraged
her daughters

00:37:26.610 --> 00:37:29.150
to continue their art and work.

00:37:29.150 --> 00:37:32.650
Her father and brothers follow
Minera's mother's lead defending

00:37:32.650 --> 00:37:34.960
Minera and her two sisters.

00:37:34.960 --> 00:37:38.490
As a result, the family
was assaulted many times.

00:37:38.490 --> 00:37:42.260
Their lives were threatened
so they chose to flee.

00:37:42.260 --> 00:37:45.480
Minera is an accomplished
actor, director and playwright.

00:37:45.480 --> 00:37:47.580
Her two sisters are actors.

00:37:47.580 --> 00:37:50.810
One brother is a filmmaker,
the other a musician.

00:37:50.810 --> 00:37:56.730 position:56%
Today, Minera travels to perform
her one person play called Sitahara,

00:37:56.730 --> 00:38:00.930
The Stars, which she wrote
after she moved to Sweden.

00:38:00.930 --> 00:38:04.680
It is a story about three women
and their sufferings in Afghanistan

00:38:04.680 --> 00:38:08.610
from 130 years ago to now.

00:38:08.610 --> 00:38:11.110
This is Arnchorn Pon
[assumed spelling]

00:38:11.110 --> 00:38:14.880
who is an a musician
living in Cambodia.

00:38:14.880 --> 00:38:18.690
Arn came from a family who
opened an opera company.

00:38:18.690 --> 00:38:21.680
When the Khmer Rouge
took power in the 1970's,

00:38:21.680 --> 00:38:24.900
they targeted artists
sending them to the camps

00:38:24.900 --> 00:38:27.270
and killing many of them.

00:38:27.270 --> 00:38:30.860
Arn was sent to a camp where
he learned how to play music.

00:38:30.860 --> 00:38:33.730
He says music saved his life.

00:38:33.730 --> 00:38:38.130
While in the camp, he was made to
play for the Khmer Rouge guards

00:38:38.130 --> 00:38:41.320
and while victims were
being tortured and killed.

00:38:41.320 --> 00:38:45.390
He eventually was given a rifle
like many boys sent into the jungle

00:38:45.390 --> 00:38:49.350
to kill the Khmer Rouge
at the Thai border.

00:38:49.350 --> 00:38:53.780
He fled escaping to a refugee
camp where he met an American man.

00:38:53.780 --> 00:38:57.410
The man took Arn back to New
Hampshire and adopted him.

00:38:57.410 --> 00:39:02.640
After a full education, Arn started
Cambodia Living Arts to support

00:39:02.640 --> 00:39:05.730
and educate Cambodians,
teaching them music

00:39:05.730 --> 00:39:08.350
and giving them a better life.

00:39:08.350 --> 00:39:11.630
He now lives in Cambodia.

00:39:11.630 --> 00:39:16.030
Tin Lin was born and raised
in Burma, now Myanmar,

00:39:16.030 --> 00:39:18.810
where his father owned a saw mill.

00:39:18.810 --> 00:39:22.640
Tin Lin began painting as a boy,
attending [inaudible] University

00:39:22.640 --> 00:39:27.410
where he studied law and supported
himself as a comedian and actor.

00:39:27.410 --> 00:39:31.070
One of thousands of Burmese
arrested, Tin Lin was thrown

00:39:31.070 --> 00:39:35.010
into prison for protesting
against the repressive government.

00:39:35.010 --> 00:39:40.720
He was political prisoner
from 1998 until 2004.

00:39:40.720 --> 00:39:46.260
While confined often in solitary
confinement in the Mandolay prison,

00:39:46.260 --> 00:39:50.510
Tin Lin persuaded guards with whom
he became friendly to purchase

00:39:50.510 --> 00:39:53.160
and smuggle in paints for him.

00:39:53.160 --> 00:39:58.180
He used items in the prison like
bowls, syringes, cigarette lighters

00:39:58.180 --> 00:40:03.580
in the absence of brushes to make
paintings and monoprints of cotton,

00:40:03.580 --> 00:40:06.320
prison uniforms like this.

00:40:06.320 --> 00:40:12.850 position:56%
Working at night and for two hours
at a time while friendly guards were

00:40:12.850 --> 00:40:18.280
on duty, he used bars of soap
and sculpted images of cellmates

00:40:18.280 --> 00:40:20.210
and painted the prison surroundings

00:40:20.210 --> 00:40:23.710
and the suffering faces
of fellow prisoners.

00:40:23.710 --> 00:40:28.880
Tin Lin successfully arranged to
smuggle more than 300 paintings

00:40:28.880 --> 00:40:32.840
and sculptures out of the
prison, which were later deposited

00:40:32.840 --> 00:40:36.810
in the International Institute
of Social History in Amsterdam.

00:40:36.810 --> 00:40:43.440
On 12/12/2012, Tin Lin was one
of 80 artists from 24 countries

00:40:43.440 --> 00:40:48.340
who participated in the first
annual [inaudible] in Indian.

00:40:48.340 --> 00:40:54.110
Tin Lin's multimedia artwork
called The Special Court,

00:40:54.110 --> 00:40:57.960
was installed in Mandolay Hall in
the Jewish quarter of [inaudible].

00:40:57.960 --> 00:41:01.740
The installation based on
Tin Lin's written story

00:41:01.740 --> 00:41:04.130
about his sentencing
in the Mandolay prison.

00:41:04.130 --> 00:41:10.800
In July, 2013, Tin Lin returned
with his family to live in Burma

00:41:10.800 --> 00:41:14.860
to take advantage of the
new reforms in his country.

00:41:14.860 --> 00:41:19.740 position:56%
He is currently working on a show of
hands capturing in plaster the hands

00:41:19.740 --> 00:41:23.610
of thousands of former
political prisoners in Burma.

00:41:23.610 --> 00:41:27.270
So far, he has completed
more than 400.

00:41:27.270 --> 00:41:31.560
The show of hands represents how
Burma was once broken and now

00:41:31.560 --> 00:41:35.030
in the process of healing, and
it is also about the process

00:41:35.030 --> 00:41:39.770
of engaging the community through
performance and public art.

00:41:39.770 --> 00:41:42.290
This was Johan Belmar
[assumed spelling].

00:41:42.290 --> 00:41:45.440
He's a visual artist
working in mixed media.

00:41:45.440 --> 00:41:49.950
He was born in Chile and now lives
here in Tacoma Park, Maryland.

00:41:49.950 --> 00:41:53.600
As a young boy, Johan grew up
in Chile under the dictatorship

00:41:53.600 --> 00:41:57.410
of Pinochet in the
1970's, 80's and 90's.

00:41:57.410 --> 00:41:59.920
His mother worked in a factory.

00:41:59.920 --> 00:42:02.650
One day Johan remembers
walking over a bridge

00:42:02.650 --> 00:42:04.910
where he saw bodies floating.

00:42:04.910 --> 00:42:09.320
As he got older, aware that he
was gay and had a strong design

00:42:09.320 --> 00:42:13.770
and artistic talent, he knew he
was going to have to leave Chile

00:42:13.770 --> 00:42:17.750
because the penalty for
homosexuality was death.

00:42:17.750 --> 00:42:21.550
Expressing one's artistic
ideas was risky.

00:42:21.550 --> 00:42:27.070
In 1995, leaving his homeland
and his family, he fled to Spain

00:42:27.070 --> 00:42:30.360
where he experienced
freedom for the first time.

00:42:30.360 --> 00:42:34.100
Later, Johan came to the
U.S. and became a citizen.

00:42:34.100 --> 00:42:37.270
In the last year, Johan
has exhibited his works

00:42:37.270 --> 00:42:41.060
at the Addison Ripley Fine Art
in D.C. and the McClain Project

